Here's the full picture:

CONFIG_IA64_GENERIC was a "System type" choice option meaning "build a kernel that supports all platforms at boot time via machvec runtime selection." When SN2 was removed, the entire System type choice menu was deleted. The DIG-like defaults were baked directly into the always-on config IA64 with unconditional select ACPI, select SWIOTLB, select PCI_MSI, etc.

Our v4 patches do NOT define CONFIG_IA64_GENERIC anywhere. It evaluates as undefined/false in all contexts. This has three consequences:

    sn2/io.c — its entire body is inside #ifdef CONFIG_IA64_GENERIC, so it compiles to an empty object. This is correct for our approach — those were function pointer wrappers for the machvec dispatch table. We use the ___sn_* inlines directly via io.h #defines instead.
    Driver guards like defined(CONFIG_IA64_GENERIC) || defined(CONFIG_IA64_SGI_SN2) — these all work fine because the SN2 side fires.
    Kconfig depends on (IA64_SGI_SN2 || IA64_GENERIC) — works fine, Kconfig treats undefined symbols as n, so this evaluates to (y || n) = y.

One thing worth flagging: the clean v5.4 config IA64 unconditionally selects SWIOTLB. The v3 patches removed that and made it per-platform (SN2 didn't select SWIOTLB since it has its own DMA via SHUB). Our v4 keeps the unconditional select SWIOTLB, meaning SN2 builds will have SWIOTLB compiled in and its bounce buffer initialized even though SN2 never uses it. This wastes ~64MB of memory but shouldn't cause a functional problem — SN2's sn_setup() sets its own dma_ops. If you want to reclaim that memory, we could make select SWIOTLB conditional on !IA64_SGI_SN2. Want me to add that?

